@endnode

@node "Win_Font" "Font"

@endnode

@node "Menu_Arexx" "Arexx"



    GUIToolKit has an arexx port called "GUITLREXX" you can write scripts
    and execute them directly from this program via the menu item
    "Arexx/ExecuteScript".  You can also set up 10 menu items to execute 
    scripts directly with "Arexx/SetUp".

    Here is a list of the arexx commands so far, I hope to extend this 
    in the future -

    @{u}Gadgets@{uu}

    NoOfGadgets   returns the value in RESULT 
    GadgetX
    GadgetY
    GadgetType 

    MoveGadget <Index>,<XOffset>,<YOffset>
    SizeGadget <Index>,<AddToWidth>,<AddToHeight>

    @{u}Borders@{uu}
 
    NoOfBorders   returns the value in RESULT

    AddBorder <X>,<Y>,<Width>,<Height>
    MoveBorder <Index>,<X>,<Y> 

    @{u}Text@{uu}

    LinesOfText   returns the value in RESULT
    
    AddText <Text>,<X>,<Y>

    @{u}Misc@{uu}

    Quit
    Version
    @{"UpdateDisplay" link "Arexx_UpDateDisplay" 0}
@endnode

@node "Menu_AddGadgets" "Gadgets"



     To add a gadget to your window simply select the type of gadget you
     want from this menu list.  Then press the LMB at the start position
     of the gadget and holding the LMB down, drag a box out to the final
     size you want.  
     Then a window will pop up enabling you to alter various settings
     of the gadget you have created.
@endnode

@node "Arexx_UpDateDisplay" "UpdateDisplay"


        When your script has finished running you will need to add this 
   command at the end of your script in order to see the result.
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_Gad_Copy" "Copy"



    
   Click on this gadget @{i}@{fg shadow}or@{ui}@{fg text} press 'C' and then click on any gadget in your 
   window @{i}@{fg shadow}(number and text gadgets cannot normally be selected however you
   may select them in GUIToolKit be clicking the upper left hand corner of 
   the gadget)@{ui}@{fg text} a floating outline of that gadget will appear
   under the mouse pointer, move to the required position and click LMB.
   the edit requester for that gadget will appear with identical values 
   allready filled in (only the x & y values will be different)
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_Gad_Edit" "Edit"


   Click on this gadget @{i}@{fg shadow}or@{ui}@{fg text} press 'E' and then click on any gadget in your 
   window @{i}@{fg shadow}(number and text gadgets cannot normally be selected however you
   may select them in GUIToolKit be clicking the upper left hand corner of 
   the gadget)@{ui}@{fg text} this will bring up the same requester window as when you
   created the gadget originaly.
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_Gad_Move" "Move"


   Click on this gadget @{i}@{fg shadow}or@{ui}@{fg text} press 'M' and then click on any gadget in your 
   window @{i}@{fg shadow}(number and text gadgets cannot normally be selected however you
   may select them in GUIToolKit be clicking the upper left hand corner of 
   the gadget)@{ui}@{fg text} that gadget will be highlighted and if the
   shift key is held down then you can drag a box around several gadgets .
   When released a requester window will appear, if you have selected more 
   than one gadget then you have to specify the x & y values to move all
   the selected gadgets.  If you have only selected one gadget then you
   have the additional option of using the mouse, a 'floating box' will 
   appear under the mouse  pointer, simply move to the required position 
   then click LMB.
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_Gad_Size" "Size"
   


   Click on this gadget @{i}@{fg shadow}or@{ui}@{fg text} press 'S' and then click on any gadget in your 
   window @{i}@{fg shadow}(number and text gadgets cannot normally be selected however you
   may select them in GUIToolKit be clicking the upper left hand corner of 
   the gadget)@{ui}@{fg text} and hold, a 'rubber band' will appear under the mouse
   pointer simply stretch to the dessired size then release LMB.
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_Gad_Del" "Del"



   Click on this gadget @{i}@{fg shadow}or@{ui}@{fg text} press 'D' and then click on any gadget in your 
   window @{i}@{fg shadow}(number and text gadgets cannot normally be selected however you
   may select them in GUIToolKit be clicking the upper left hand corner of 
   the gadget)@{ui}@{fg text} a comfirmation requester will appear then the
   gadget will be removed.
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_Borders_Add" "Add"



   To add borders around groups of gadgets click on this gadget on the 
   tool-bar.  Then click LMB once and hold for the starting position and
   drag out to the dessired size.
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_GadId" "Gads Id"



    This integer gadget displays the ID of any gadget clicked on in 
    your project window.  This is usefull if you need to change the
    ID's for any reason to fit in with the rest of your program 
    code.
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_Borders_Edit" "Edit"



   Click this gadget and a second toolbar will appear at the bottom of the
   screen.  This will enable you to manipulate the @{i}highlighted border@{ui} in
   your window.  Select the border to work on using the @{i}next@{ui} button.
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_Text_Add" "Add"



    You can add text directly onto your window by selecting this button
    from the 'Tool-bar'.
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_Text_Edit" "Edit"



   This button will bring up a second window which will enable your to
   alter, add, move and delete lines of text.  Select the line to work
   on from the list.
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_Re-Num" "Re-num gads Id"



      If your click on this gadget all the gadgets in your window
      will have there ID's re-numbered consecutivly starting at '1'.
      This is for when you have done a lot of editing/deleting/adding 
      gadgets in a project and simply want the ID's neatly re-aliened
      in the generated code.
@endnode

@node "ToolBar_ListGads" "List"


      Here you will find a list displaying all the gadgets you have created
      so far, which is an exact copy of the lines of code that will be
      generated not including any "Tags".  You can perform a number of 
      operations on them simply select any line and click on the buttons 
      below.

      1.  MoveUp will move the selected line up one line in the list
          and simularly MoveDown will do the opposite. 
      2.  Edit will bring up the corrisponding editor window for that
          gadget.
      3.  Move will allow you to move the selected gadget.
      4.  Size will allow you to re-size the selected gadget. 
      5.  Delete will allow you to delete the selected gadget.
      6.  Sort will attempt to sort the gadgets into ascending order 
          with respect to their Gadget Id's.
      7.  @{"ReNumber" link "ToolBar_Re-Num" 0} will re-number the Gadget Id's starting at 1 being the
          first in the list.

      If you have created any Text or Number gadgets then this is now the
      only way you can select them for edit/sizing/moving.
@endnode

@node "KeyBoard_ShortCuts" "Key board short-cuts"



     Most gadgets/options have keyboard shortcuts indicated by a letter
     in the gadgets text being underlined ie. Pa@{u}l@{uu}ette
     Also the "Ok" and "Cancil" buttons are activated by the "Return"
     and "Escape" keys respectively.
@endnode

